[[File:Hunseby kirke cropped.jpg|thumb|Hunseby Church]]
'''Hunseby Church''' is located in the village of [[Hunseby]] some 3 km north of [[Maribo]] on the [[Denmark|Danish]] island of [[Lolland]]. Built in the middle of the 12th century, the church has a [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] [[chancel]] and [[nave]] and a [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] tower.<ref name=ha>[http://historiskatlas.dk/Hunseby_kirke_(5923) "Hunseby Church"], ''Historisk Atlas''. {{da icon}} Retrieved 3 July 2013.</ref>
==History== The church was originally dedicated to [[Andrew the Apostle|St Andrew]] as can be seen from the inscription on the oldest bell from 1465. From Romanesque inscriptions in the stonework supporting an old portal, it appears the church must have existed in the middle of the 12th century. Little is known of its early ownership apart from the fact that the Crown had appointment rights shortly before the [[Danish Reformation|Reformation]]. It remained the property of the Crown until 1565 when it was transferred to Axel Urne til Aarsmarke. One of the later owners was Eggert Christopher Knuth who was married to Sister Lerche. It came under the authority of [[Knuthenborg]] when the county was established by Sister Lerche in 1714. In April 1964, it gained its independence.<ref name=natmus>[http://www.natmus.dk/uploads/tx_tcchurchsearch/Maribo_0905-0922_01.pdf Kirsten Weber-Andersen, Otto Norn, Aage Roussell, Gertrud Købke Knudsen, "Hunsby Kirke"], ''Danmarks kirker: Maribo amt, Volume 8'', 1951, Nationalmuseet, pages 905-922. {{da icon}} Retrieved 11 July 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.visitlolland-falster.com/ln-int/danmark/bicycle-route---maribobandholm-gdk616569 "Bicycle route - Maribo/Bandholm"], Visit Lolland-Falster. Retrieved 11 July 2013.</ref>
==Architecture== Built of fine granite stonework, the Romanesque church is unusually large. The outer walls are plastered and whitewashed while the roof is of red tile. The chancel has retained its Romanesque windows. Compared to the chancel, the nave is higher and wider. A sculpted head on the south wall is said to be King Huns's head, in line with the legend behind the name of the village. The Gothic tower is in red brick with some granite stonework and stepped gables. The [[Knuthenborg]] burial chapel was added on the south side of the church in 1851 and completely rebuilt in 1880.<ref name=natmus/>
==Interior== The round chancel arch has rope-shaped corbels while the chancel ceiling was vaulted in the Gothic period. The [[Auricular style|Auricular Baroque]] [[altarpiece]] is from c. 1700 with a painting of the Last Supper and the arms of Eggert Christopher Knuth and Sister Lerche. The [[pulpit]], in the [[Renaissance|High Renaissance]] style, is from 1617 and bears the arms of Knud Urne and Merete Grubbe.<ref name=natmus/><ref>[http://www.nordenskirker.dk/Tidligere/Hunseby_kirke/Hunseby_kirke.htm "Hunseby kirke"], ''Nordens kirker''. {{da icon}} Retrieved 11 July 2013.</ref> In the burial chapel, there is an epitaph for Eggert Christopher Knuth (died 1697) and Sister Lerche (died 1723).<ref name=ha/>
