{{Infobox newspaper | name = New Directions for Women | logo = | image = | caption = | type = Quarterly newspaper and Drug and Alcohol Rehabilitation for women, women with children and pregnant women. | format = [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|Tabloid]] [[Addiction Treatment Center (newspaper format)|Facility]] | owners = | founder = | publisher = | president = | editor = [[Paula Kassell]] | chief editor = | assistant editor = | maneditor = | generalmanager = | newseditor = | staff = [[Sue Bright, Executive Director]] [[Tania Bhattacharyya, Foundation Executive Director]] | foundation = {{start date|1972|01}} {{start date|1977|01}} | political = | language = | ceased publication = {{end date|1993}} {{end date|ongoing}} | relaunched = | headquarters = [[Dover, New Jersey]] [[Costa mesa, California]] | circulation = | sister newspapers = | ISSN = | oclc = | RNI = | website = https://www.newdirectionsforwomen.org | free = | dirinteractive = }} '''''New Directions for Women''''' was an important early [[feminism|feminist]] newspaper. It began as a [[mimeograph]]ed newsletter in 1972 in [[New Jersey]], but soon expanded into a tabloid-sized quarterly newspaper. Edited by Paula Kassell of Dover, a member of the Morristown chapter of [[National Organization for Women]] (NOW), the paper offered news reports from a feminist perspective as well as book reviews, [[women's history]] articles, and editorials, and was the first national feminist newspaper in the United States. After years of struggling to attain financial stability, the newspaper discontinued publishing in 1993.<ref name="shs">{{cite web|url=http://shs.umsystem.edu/manuscripts/invent/4031.pdf|title=Records of New Directions for Women|publisher=[[State Historical Society of Missouri]]|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref><ref>Townsend, Cara. [http://www.dailyrecord.com/article/20120901/NJNEWS/309010018/Paula-Kassell-feminist-pioneer-Dover-resident-dies-94 "Paula Kassell, feminist pioneer and Dover resident, dies at 94"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130120062244/http://www.dailyrecord.com/article/20120901/NJNEWS/309010018/Paula-Kassell-feminist-pioneer-Dover-resident-dies-94 |date=2013-01-20 }}, ''[[Daily Record (Morristown)]]'', September 1, 2012. Accessed September 5, 2012. "Kassell was a long-time women’s rights activist who in 1972 founded the news tabloid, New Directions for Women, and later convinced the New York Times to use Ms. in addition to Miss and Mrs. on the paper's pages."</ref> This was five years before Pamela Wilder founded the [[non-profit organization|non-profit]] [https://www.newdirectionsforwomen.org drug rehab] "[https://www.newdirectionsforwomen.org/about-us/history/ New Directions for Women]" in 1977 through the [[Junior League]] of Orange County. New Directions for Women is still helping women, pregnant women, and their children find recovery.
